(1.) For the Quomodo, in the firſt place; Whatſoever we do, we muſt do it from the Heart which requires theſe three properties at leaſt. (1.) That we do it with Knowledge. (2.) With Freedom. (3.) With Conſcience to God, and no other: The Will and 
                  Ʋnderſtanding (being the two parts of the Soul) require the two firſt;


and the natural bent and verticity of the Soul after God, (its only center and reſt) requires the laſt: For nothing is, or can be ſaid, to be done from the heart, which is not done for God, and before him: An honeſt hearty man, doth all, that he doth, as it were, upon his oath, becauſe he doth every thing from his heart, and Conſcience, in the preſence of God.
